frameDefinitions: This scenario describes a series of Events, associated with a single Participant, i.e., the history of the Participant.
Words in this frame name the different parts of the calendric cycle, both man-made and natural.
The Military of a Possessor (either a nation, institution, or private individual) conducts large-scale activities in a Area to accomplish military or combined military/non-military goals.
An Event is identified as occurring at a particular Distance and in a particular Direction from a Landmark_event.
A Trajector is identified as occurring at the same time as some better-known Landmark.
These words relate to the relative ordering of two events or times.
frameExamples: We've been worried about our recent hire's <t><fex name='Events'>history</fex></t> of deceiving employers.
Jo's mother will visit on this coming <t>Tuesday</t>.
These groups are known to have carried out attacks on international coalition forces <t>operating</t> in Afghanistan.
Tell me that a week <t>from</t> now.
He tried to take care of that <t>on</t> his last visit .
<t>After</t> she arrived , she laid out her papers on the desk.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Participant</fen> is either an active participant in all of the <fen>Events</fen> (e.g., Agent or Patient), or is more peripherally associated with the <fen>Events</fen> (e.g., Location or Topic).
The <fen>Events</fen> which the <fen>Participant</fen> is a part of. This role is used to mark the frame-evoking element.
When the <fen>Events</fen> concerning the <fen>Participant</fen> occured.
<fen>Relative_time</fen> is used for the word or words that locate the time with respect to an identifiable reference point.
<fen>Whole</fen> is used for the larger unit of which the target word names a part.
The calendric unit that is denoted. LUs in this frame all denote the <fen>Unit</fen>.
The <fen>Force</fen> carries out the operation. Depending on the size of the operation, this may be as few as one individual or as large as the armed forces of a nation.
The <fen>Area</fen> in which the <fen>Military</fen> is conducting operations.
The nation, group, or situation which the operation opposes.
The <fen>Goal</fen> of the operation.
The <fen>Time</fen> at which the operations are carried out.
The location of the operation.
This Frame Element marks expressions that indicate the reference point in which the Event  is anchored.
This role marks expressions that indicate the amount of time that lies between the Target and the <fen>Landmark_event</fen>.
This role marks expressions that indicate whether the Target is prior or subsequent to the <fen>Landmark_event</fen> on the time line.
This role indicates the <fen>Event</fen> temporally located with respect to the <fen>Landmark_event</fen>.
The entity that occurs at some time.
The event which designates the time at which a trajector occurs.
The period that occurs with respect to some other time.
The period in which a trajector takes place.  This period can be cyclical and, in that case, is interpreted contextually.
The event that occurs at some time.
The entity which designates the time of some trajector.  Note: this role is infrequent or non-existent in English and is included for completeness.

The <fen>Focal_occasion</fen> is the event which is  being located in time with respect to some other event: The <fen>Focal_occasion</fen> is profiled, in contrast to the <fen>Landmark_occasion</fen>, which is backgrounded.
The <fen>Landmark_occasion</fen> is the event  with respect to which the <fen>Focal_occasion</fen> is located.
The <fen>Focal_participant</fen> is the participant in the <fen>Focal_occasion</fen> which is profiled as being in a relation of relative time to the <fen>Landmark_occasion</fen>.
